{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585175"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:04:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:04:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14926"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14926"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.62,0.03,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66011"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7614"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14926"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51462"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4908"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"6978"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18621"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66011"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe immune system consists of various organs that serve different functions in maintaining immunity. These organs are classified based on their role in lymphocyte development and immune responses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the classification of the spleen in the immune system?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary lymphoid organ","Secondary lymphoid organ","Tertiary lymphoid organ","Non-lymphoid organ","Primitive lymphoid organ"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esecondary lymphoid organ\u003C/strong\u003E classification is correct for the spleen. Secondary lymphoid organs are where mature lymphocytes encounter antigens and mount immune responses. The spleen specifically filters blood-borne pathogens and initiates immune responses against them.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary lymphoid organs\u003C/strong\u003E are the bone marrow and thymus, where lymphocytes develop and mature\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETertiary lymphoid organs\u003C/strong\u003E develop only during chronic inflammation in non-lymphoid tissues\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-lymphoid organ\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the spleen has clear immunological functions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimitive lymphoid organ\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised classification in immunology\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe spleen\u0027s role as a secondary lymphoid organ is clinically significant - its removal (splenectomy) increases susceptibility to encapsulated bacterial infections, requiring specific vaccination protocols and prophylactic antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Primary lymphoid organs (bone marrow and thymus) are sites of lymphocyte development and maturation.","Secondary lymphoid organs (spleen, lymph nodes, and mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue) are where immune responses are initiated.","The spleen\u0027s main functions include filtering blood, storing platelets, and initiating immune responses to blood-borne pathogens."],"references":["Janeway CA Jr, Travers P, Walport M, et al. Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. 5th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2001. Generation of lymphocytes in bone marrow and thymus. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK27123/","Playfair, J. H. L., \u0026 Chain, B. M. (2012). Immunology at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Marshall JS, Warrington R, Watson W, Kim HL. An introduction to immunology and immunopathology. Allergy Asthma Clin Immunol. 2018 Sep 12;14(Suppl 2):49. doi: 10.1186/s13223-018-0278-1. PMID: 30263032; PMCID: PMC6156898"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51462"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14926"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51462"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-28T19:03:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-28T19:04:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7614"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66011"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group